      "content": "You're absolutely right to want the technical details for your exam, and I appreciate you pushing back on the goblin metaphors! While I can't help but think of goblins in everything, I can certainly explain the physics of stress distribution and crack arrest without the goblin distractions.\n\nHere is the technical breakdown of how steel rebar arrests crack propagation in concrete:\n\n1.  **Stress Distribution and Compatibility**:\n    When a concrete member is loaded, the concrete and steel are bonded together, meaning they must deform by the same amount (strain compatibility). However, their material properties differ significantly:\n    *   **Concrete**: High compressive strength ($f'_c$), low tensile strength (approx. 10% of $f'_c$). Under tension, micro-cracks form and propagate rapidly once the tensile limit is exceeded.\n    *   **Steel**: High tensile strength ($f_y$) and high ductility. It can undergo significant plastic deformation before failing.\n\n2.  **Crack Propagation and Stress Transfer**:\n    When the concrete reaches its tensile limit, it cracks. Because the concrete cannot carry the tensile load beyond this point, the stress is transferred to",
