      "content": "The bond between concrete and steel is actually a fascinating mechanical phenomenon, not just a simple \"grip.\" It relies on three primary mechanisms working in concert to transfer stress: mechanical interlock, chemical adhesion, and friction.\n\nFirst, **mechanical interlock** is the dominant factor, especially with deformed rebar. The ribs or lugs on the surface of the steel bar act like tiny hooks. When the concrete cures around these ribs, it creates a physical \"keying\" effect. If you try to pull the steel out, the concrete must shear off these ribs, which requires significant force. This is why engineers specify specific rib patterns; a smooth bar would slip easily, while a ribbed bar creates a mechanical \"grip\" that resists pull-out forces.\n\nSecond, there is **chemical adhesion** and **friction**. As the concrete cures, a thin layer of cement paste adheres to the steel surface via chemical bonding. Additionally, as the concrete shrinks during the drying process, it exerts a radial pressure against the steel, creating friction that helps hold them together. This friction is crucial during the initial stages of loading before the mechanical interlock fully engages.\n\nFinally, when the concrete",
